Rani Lakshmi Bai was the queen of the princely state of Jhansi in India, known for her bravery and leadership during the Indian Rebellion of 1857. She is considered a national heroine in India and a symbol of resistance against British colonial rule. Born on November 19, 1828, she was married to Raja Gangadhar Rao, the king of Jhansi, and became the queen after his death. When the British East India Company attempted to annex Jhansi, Rani Lakshmi Bai refused to surrender and led her army in a fierce battle against the British. She died on June 18, 1858, during the battle, but her legacy lives on as a legendary figure in Indian history.
